REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emOwnPtr.h: unique-ownership smart pointer (pre-C++11 unique_ptr).

17 files outside emCore use this type.

C++ defines these types:
  emOwnPtrBase<OBJ, DELETER>  — base class with ownership transfer
  emOwnPtr<OBJ>               — single-object ownership (delete)
  emOwnArrayPtr<OBJ>          — array ownership (delete[])
  emOwnPtrDeleter<OBJ>        — single-object deleter functor
  emOwnArrayPtrDeleter<OBJ>   — array deleter functor

Method mapping (verified — identical functionality, different names):
  constructor(ptr)  -> Some(Box::new(value))
  Set(ptr) / op=    -> field = Some(Box::new(value))
  Reset()           -> field = None
  Release()         -> field.take()
  Get() / op->      -> field.as_ref() / field.as_deref()
  op OBJECT*()      -> implicit deref via Deref trait or .as_ref()

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  emOwnPtrBase / emOwnPtrDeleter / emOwnArrayPtrDeleter — Rust's Drop
    trait handles deallocation. No explicit deleter types exist.
  emOwnArrayPtr<OBJ> as a distinct type — Rust uses Vec<T> for owned
    arrays. The delete[] vs delete distinction does not exist in Rust.

Rust equivalents used in the codebase (verified by grep):
  emOwnPtr<T>         -> Option<Box<T>>
    emColorField.rs:87      — Option<Box<Expansion>>
    emEngine.rs:41          — Option<Box<dyn emEngine>>
    emViewAnimator.rs:30-31 — Option<Box<dyn emViewAnimator>>
    emWindow.rs:54          — Option<Box<dyn emViewAnimator>>
  emOwnArrayPtr<T>    -> Vec<T>
    (emFileStream.h:110 uses emOwnArrayPtr<emByte> — equivalent is Vec<u8>)

